HEADWORD: Torse
<hw>Torse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF., fr. OF. & F.
<ets>tors</ets>, <ets>torse</ets>, twisted, wreathed, p. p. of
<ets>tordre</ets> to twist, L. <ets>torquere</ets>. See
<er>Torture</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A wreath.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[F. <ets>tors</ets>, <ets>torse</ets>,
twisted.]</ety> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A developable surface. See under
<er>Developable</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Torsel</ent>⟦br⟧
